1 - AMMI Model

The model is formulated as \[y_{ij} = \mu + g_i + e_j + \sum\limits_{q = 1}^Q \lambda_q\gamma_{iq}\delta_{jq} + \epsilon_{ij},\] where \(\epsilon_{ij}\sim N(0,\sigma^2_y)\). We have two formulations:

Parameter Josse’s Crossa’s
\(\mu\) \(N(\mu_mu, \sigma^2_\mu)\) \(N(\mu_mu, \sigma^2_\mu)\)
\(g_i\) \(N(0,\sigma^2_g)\) \(N(\mu_g,\sigma^2_g)\)
\(e_j\) \(N(0,\sigma^2_e)\) \(N(\mu_e,\sigma^2_e)\)
\(\lambda_q\) \(N^+(0,\sigma^2_\lambda)\) \(N^+(\mu_\lambda,\sigma^2_\lambda)\)
\(\gamma_{iq}\) \(N^+(0,1)\), i = 1; \(N(0,1)\), \(i>1\), q = 1,…,Q spherical uniform
\(\delta_{jq}\) \(N(0,1)\) spherical uniform
\(\sigma^2_y\) \(U(0,s^2_{\sigma^2_y})\) \(Inv-Scaled-\chi^2(a,b)\)

For both approaches , \(\lambda_q>0\) and \(\lambda_{q-1}\geq\lambda_q\). In our formulation, we consider \(\sigma^2_y \sim \Gamma(a,b)\). In order to meet the model constraints, we perform the following procedure on the bilinear term. Let \(\theta^{\gamma}_{iq} \sim N(0,\sigma^\theta)\), for \(i = 1, ..., I-1\), and \(\theta^{\gamma}_{Iq} = -\sum\limits_{i\neq I}\theta^{\gamma}_{iq}\). Similarly, let \(\theta^{\delta}_{jq} \sim N(0,\sigma^\theta)\), for \(j = 1, ..., J-1\), and \(\theta^{\delta}_{Jq} = -\sum\limits_{j\neq J}\theta^{\delta}_{jq}\). Then, \[\gamma_{iq} = \frac{\theta^\gamma_{iq}}{\sqrt{\sum\limits_{i} \theta^{\gamma^2}_{iq}}}\] \[\delta_{jq} = \frac{\theta^\delta_{jq}}{\sqrt{\sum\limits_{j} \theta^{\delta^2}_{jq}}}\]

1.1 - Results

1.1.1 \(\sigma^2_\theta = 1\)

1.1.1.1 Q = 1

1.1.2 Q = 2

1.1.3 \(\sigma^2_\theta = 100\)

1.1.3.1 Q = 1

1.1.4 Q = 2

2 - BAMMIT Model

The BAMMIT model is formulated as \[y_{ijk} = \mu + g_i + e_j + t_k + \sum\limits_{q = 1}^Q \lambda_q\gamma_{iq}\delta_{jq}\kappa_{kq} + \epsilon_{ijk},\]

where \(\epsilon_{ijk}\sim N(0,\sigma^2_y)\), \(i = 1,..., I\), \(j = 1, ..., J\) and \(k = 1, ..., K\). We Assume that

\[\mu\sim N(\mu_\mu, \sigma^2_\mu)\]
\[g_i\sim N(\mu_g,\sigma^2_g)\]
\[e_j\sim N(\mu_e,\sigma^2_e)\]
\[t_k\sim N(\mu_t,\sigma^2_t)\]
\[\lambda_q \sim N^+(\mu_\lambda,\sigma^2_\lambda)\]
\[\sigma^2_y\sim \Gamma(a,b)\]

For the parameters \(\gamma_{iq}\), \(\delta_{jq}\) and \(\kappa_{kq}\) we follow as before. Let \[\theta^{\gamma}_{iq} \sim N(0,\sigma^\theta), i = 1, ..., I-1,\] \[\theta^{\gamma}_{Iq} = -\sum\limits_{i\neq I}\theta^{\gamma}_{iq}\] \[\theta^{\delta}_{jq} \sim N(0,\sigma^\theta), j = 1, ..., J-1,\] \[\theta^{\delta}_{Jq} = -\sum\limits_{j\neq J}\theta^{\delta}_{jq};\] \[\theta^{\kappa}_{kq} \sim N(0,\sigma^\theta), k = 1, ..., K-1,\] \[\theta^{\kappa}_{Kq} = -\sum\limits_{k\neq K}\theta^{\kappa}_{kq};\]
